# The Syntax Rules üìè

A CSS rule-set consists of a **selector** and a **declaration block**.

```css
h1 {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 12px;
}
```

- **Selector (`h1`):** Points to the HTML element you want to style.
- **Property (`color`):** The style attribute you want to change.
- **Value (`blue`):** The new setting for the property.
- **Declaration:** `property: value;` always ends with a semicolon.

# Element Selector üéØ

The element selector selects HTML elements based on the **element name**.

```css
p {
  text-align: center;
  color: red;
}
```

All `<p>` elements on the page will be centered and red.

# Id Selector üÜî

The id selector uses the `id` attribute of an HTML element to select a **specific** element.

- The id of an element is unique within a page.
- To select an element with a specific id, write a hash (`#`) character, followed by the id of the element.

```css
#para1 {
  text-align: center;
  color: red;
}
```

# Class Selector üè´

The class selector selects HTML elements with a specific `class` attribute.

- To select elements with a specific class, write a period (`.`) character, followed by the class name.

```css
.center {
  text-align: center;
  color: red;
}
```

You can also specify that only specific HTML elements should be affected by a class:
```css
p.center {
  text-align: center;
  color: red;
}
```

# Universal Selector üåå

The universal selector (`*`) selects **all** HTML elements on the page.

```css
* {
  text-align: center;
  color: blue;
}
```

Often used for resetting margins and padding:
```css
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

# Grouping Selectors üëØ

If you have elements with the same style definitions, you can group them.

Seperate each selector with a comma.

```css
h1, h2, p {
  text-align: center;
  color: red;
}
```
This code minimizes the CSS needed.

# CSS Comments üí¨

Comments are used to explain the code, and may help when you edit the source code at a later date.

Comments are ignored by browsers.

A CSS comment starts with `/*` and ends with `*/`.

```css
/* This is a single-line comment */
p {
  color: red;
}

/* This is
a multi-line
comment */
```

# CSS Colors üé®

Colors are specified using predefined color names, or RGB, HEX, HSL, RGBA, HSLA values.

```css
/* Color Names */
h1 { color: Tomato; }

/* Hex */
p { color: #ff6347; }

/* RGB */
div { background-color: rgb(255, 99, 71); }

/* RGBA (with opacity) */
span { color: rgba(255, 99, 71, 0.5); }
```

# Backgrounds üñºÔ∏è

CSS background properties are used to define the background effects for elements.

- `background-color`
- `background-image`
- `background-repeat`
- `background-attachment`
- `background-position`

```css
body {
  background-image: url("paper.gif");
  background-color: #cccccc;
}
```

# Borders üñºÔ∏è

The CSS border properties allow you to specify the style, width, and color of an element's border.

```css
p.dotted {border-style: dotted;}
p.dashed {border-style: dashed;}
p.solid {border-style: solid;}
p.double {border-style: double;}
```

Shorthand:
```css
/* width | style | color */
p {
  border: 5px solid red;
}
```

# Margins ‚ÜîÔ∏è

Margins are used to create space around elements, **outside** of any defined borders.

- `margin-top`
- `margin-right`
- `margin-bottom`
- `margin-left`

```css
p {
  margin-top: 100px;
  margin-bottom: 100px;
  margin-right: 150px;
  margin-left: 80px;
}
```

Shorthand:
`margin: 25px 50px 75px 100px;` (top right bottom left)

# Padding üì¶

Padding is used to create space around an element's content, **inside** of any defined borders.

- `padding-top`
- `padding-right`
- `padding-bottom`
- `padding-left`

```css
div {
  padding-top: 50px;
  padding-right: 30px;
  padding-bottom: 50px;
  padding-left: 80px;
}
```

Shorthand:
`padding: 25px 50px;` (top/bottom right/left)

# Height & Width üìè

The `height` and `width` properties are used to set the height and width of an element.

```css
div {
  height: 200px;
  width: 50%;
  background-color: powderblue;
}
```

Note: The height and width properties do not include padding, borders, or margins. They set the height/width of the area inside the padding, border, and margin of the element.
